ce:section.ce:para:
The mechanical properties of the pure PVA and PVA/PQDs nanocomposite films were evaluated by tensile testing. As illustrated in Fig. 10
                           (a) and (b), the mechanical performance of the PVA/PQDs nanocomposite films was strongly dependent on the PQDs concentration. The pure PVA film exhibited typical ductile behavior with a tensile strength of 7.4 MPa and elongation at break of 289 %. As the PQDs concentration increased to 1 wt%, the tensile strength linearly increased from 47.3 to 59.0 MPa, and the elongation at break decreased from 162.0 % to 86.0 %. This phenomenon may be caused by the strong interactions between the PQDs and PVA chains, resulting in molecular rearrangement and reordering within the amorphous regions of PVA, thereby increasing its crystallinity, as supported by the DSC, XRD, and SEM analyses [41,43,46]. The incorporation of PQDs into PVA-based nanocomposite films significantly enhances their crystallinity, resulting in a denser and more organized structural framework. This structural refinement markedly increases the stiffness of the films while preserving the molecular arrangement. The presence of nanofillers promotes tighter packing and alignment of the polymer chains, thereby bolstering the mechanical integrity and overall performance of the material. These advancements yield a more resilient composite suitable for sophisticated applications [49]. Notably, the uniform distribution of PQDs within the PVA matrix leads to a substantial increase in interfacial binding energy, enhancing Young's modulus by 96.3 % when compared to pure PVA (Table 2
                           ). The mechanical properties of these PVA-based nanocomposite films are highly contingent upon the concentration of PQDs, with the optimal formulation demonstrating a maximum tensile strength of 59.19 ± 3.2 MPa at a PQD loading of 1 %. In conclusion, a small amount of PQDs as nanofillers can effectively reinforce the PVA morphology and physical properties [50].
